The magnetic IONP (γ-Fe2O3) and DMSA modified IONP were synthesized and characterized (Fig.S1-Fig.S3, ESI). From DLS measurement the hydrodynamic size of fresh γ-Fe2O3 and thiol modified γ-Fe2O3 were found to be 95.32 nm and 90.98 nm respectively (Fig.S2). This reduction in size evidenced that aggregation among magnetic nanoparticle was removed after modification with DMSA. Further measurement of hydrodynamic size of DMSA@γ-Fe2O3 against pH shows that within pH 4–8 the HD size remains constant without any significant change (Fig. S4). N2 adsorption-desorption isotherm shows a type-3 loop with specific surface area 47.944 m2/g. BJH average pore diameter was evaluated to be 3.15 nm for the γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles (Fig. 4
                        ). In the FTIR spectrum the peak around 522 cm−1 shows the occurrence of only Fe-O bond in uncoated γ-Fe2O3, whereas in case of modified γ-Fe2O3 peaks found around 520, 1126, 1385, 1570, 2361 cm−1 corresponds to FeO, CC/CO, SH, OH respectively (Fig. 5
                        ).

Bacterial cell conserved fundamental properties of all cells and have high potential to predict environmental anomalies that can lead to ecosystem stress. Hence, bacteria have been used as an invaluable model in elucidating biochemical tests related to environmental parameters, pathogen detection etc. For a biological feasibility of the synthesized probe, the cytotoxicity of this nanoprobe was examined in E. coli and s. aureus cell. As expected the sustainability of E.coli and S. aureus is not declined upon supplement of the probe up to 250 μg mL−1 for an incubation period of 16 h (Fig. 14
                        ). Thus, the as prepared nanohybrid can be considered as risk-free and biologically acceptable and can be explored for bioimaging. We have performed cellular uptake experiment in both E.coli and S. aureus. In absence of Hg intense green signal (λex = 405 and 480 nm) of CQD appeared feeble inside both the bacterial cells (fig15
                        ). However, when the cells were added with Hg the intensity of green emission was significantly increased.

After preincubation with different concentration of Hg solution the fishes were euthanized. The gill, brain, liver and muscles where the Hg is known to be accumulated are dissected. The confocal images of different organs when supplemented with different concentrations of Hg solution show that Hg is evenly distributed in all organs. In the control sample where the fish was not fed with Hg hardly in any PL signal was observed (λex 405 nm). However, with increasing concentration of Hg the green signal intensifies clearly revealing the site of mercury accumulation (Fig. 16
                        ). The highest intensity was observed in the liver, followed by gill, brain and muscle (Fig. S10). This indicates that Hg is accumulated in the order liver > gill > brain > muscle. Therefore, our CQD-γFe2O3 integrated particle can be used as a fast fluorogenic probe to detect mercury in contaminated fish when the amounts are near about risk levels. Although, the differences in fluorescence could not be evaluated quantitatively at first sight, they gave a clear qualitative evaluation of the presence or absence of mercury in the fish samples. We further traced the amount of mercury in different organs by ICP-MS and correlated with fluorescence intensity values obtained from confocal microscopy (Table 2
                        ). From ICP-MS, it was observed that the accumulation of Hg in different tissues were prominent. Under the present experimental condition, liver was the tissue that was noticed to have the highest Hg accumulation in comparison to the other tissues. Each tissue has shown to have the gradual increase (p ≤ 0.01) in the accumulation of the Hg as a function of the concentration of exposure. In muscle tissue, the accumulation concentration of Hg was within the range 0.11 to 0.468 ppm, p ≤ 0.0001 (Fig. S11, S12a). Similarly, in brain it was within the range from 0.11 to 0.488 ppm at p ≤ 0.0001 (Fig. S12b) and in gills the range of accumulation was from 0.213 to 0.586 ppm at p ≤ 0.0001 (Fig. S12c). However, in liver, the accumulation rate was the highest being from 0.151 to 1.59 ppm at p ≤ 0.01 which is in accordance with the observation from confocal imaging (Fig. S12d).
